UNITED AIR LINES' central Mid-Continent route
is by ten years the oldest coast-to-coast airway. It
was selected by government airway engineers in 1919
as the most suitable transcontinental air route.
It parallels the famous Overland Trail, for more than
a century the principal route of coast-to-coast trans-
portation. The Covered Wagons of 1830 crossed the
great plains to the Pacific Coast along the Overland
Trail. Today, more than ever, this central route across
the continent is the Main Line and over it United flies
more traffic ton miles than are flown on any other long
distance airway in the world.
This airway was first to have plane-ground radio com-
munication, first to be lighted for night flying, first
to have weather reporting service, first to have radio
range facilities.
The central Mid-continent airway
represents outstanding developments in airline facil-
ities, and as such, it has been studied by experts
of airlines and governments the world over.
